<p>The ‘trim principle’ is that the final height coordinate at point 
 <italic>B</italic> is the minimum value among all these height coordinates induced by these tool profiles duplication. More precisely, on the current configurations in 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="micromachines-10-00288-f006">Figure 6</xref>b, the height coordinate at point 
 <italic>B</italic> is given by 
 <disp-formula id="FD5-micromachines-10-00288">
  <label>(5)</label>
  <math id="mm11">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>z</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mi>min</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>{</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>F</mi>
       <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mrow>
         <msub>
          <mi>B</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo>+</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>z</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">v</mi>
       </msub>
       <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mrow>
         <msub>
          <mi>t</mi>
          <mrow>
           <mi>Bm</mi>
          </mrow>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mi>F</mi>
       <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mrow>
         <msub>
          <mi>B</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal">M</mi>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo>+</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>z</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">v</mi>
       </msub>
       <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mrow>
         <msub>
          <mi>t</mi>
          <mrow>
           <mi>BM</mi>
          </mrow>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
      <mo>}</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <italic>F</italic>(
 <italic>B</italic>
 <sub>m</sub>) and 
 <italic>F</italic>(
 <italic>B</italic>
 <sub>M</sub>) are the height coordinates of point 
 <italic>B</italic> when the tool tip locates respectively at point 
 <italic>B</italic>
 <sub>m</sub> and 
 <italic>B</italic>
 <sub>M</sub>, which can be acquired from the theoretical models discussed in 
 <xref ref-type="sec" rid="sec2dot1-micromachines-10-00288">Section 2.1</xref>; 
 <italic>z</italic>
 <sub>v</sub>(
 <italic>t</italic>) is the vibration component at the cutting time 
 <italic>t</italic>, which will be systematically studied in the this section; 
 <italic>t</italic>
 <sub>Bm</sub> and 
 <italic>t</italic>
 <sub>BM</sub> are the corresponding times points when the diamond tool locates at the two points.
</p>
